.TH man 1 "April 2026" "1.0" "simple_shell man page"
.SH NAME
.B hsh
\- simple UNIX command interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh
[\fIfile\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX command line interpreter that reads commands from either
standard input or a file and executes them. It is a simplified version of
.BR sh (1).
.PP
When invoked without arguments,
.B hsh
reads commands from the standard input.
.SH INVOCATION
.B hsh
can be used in two modes:
.TP
.B Interactive mode
When standard input is a terminal, the shell displays a prompt
.RB ( $ )
and waits for the user to type a command, followed by a newline.
.TP
.B Non-interactive mode
When standard input is not a terminal (for example, when input is piped
or redirected from a file), the shell reads commands without displaying
a prompt and executes them line by line.
.SH BUILTINS
.B hsh
supports the following built-in commands:
.TP
.B exit
Exits the shell.
.TP
.B env
Prints the current environment, one variable per line in the form
.IR name = value .
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.B hsh
uses the
.B PATH
environment variable to locate executables when a command is entered
without a full path. Each directory in
.B PATH
is searched in order until the command is found.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.B hsh
returns the exit status of the last command executed.
If a command is not found, the exit status is 127.
On reaching end-of-file (Ctrl+D) or using the
.B exit
builtin, the shell exits with status 0.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Interactive mode:
.PP
.nf
.RS
$ ./hsh
$ ls
file1  file2  file3
$ /bin/pwd
/home/user
$ exit
.RE
.fi
.PP
Non-interactive mode:
.PP
.nf
.RS
$ echo "ls" | ./hsh
file1  file2  file3
.RE
.fi
